EXERCISE 10 on page 425:

This is an interesting problem with an easy solution.

Because one structure cannot include another before it is
declared, the code as written will not work.  To get around
the problem, we can use pointers to structures as members
rather than the structures themselves.  The compiler will
be happy with the pointers.

---
The following two lines near the top of spouse.h are examples
of incomplete types:

   struct husband;
   struct wife;

If you want to write the program without these lines,
you will have to make further changes to the header file.
Before you do this, compile and execute the program as
written so that you understand its effects.  Then remove
the above two lines and see what your compiler says.
